import librosa
import librosa.display
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# 1. Load the audio file
file_path = "test_bird_call1.mp3" # <-- Change this to your file
y, sr = librosa.load(file_path)

# 2. Create the spectrogram (the Z-axis data)
D = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(librosa.stft(y)), ref=np.max)

# 3. Create the X (time) and Y (frequency) axes
times = librosa.times_like(D, sr=sr)
frequencies = librosa.fft_frequencies(sr=sr)

# 4. Create the meshgrid for the 3D plot
X, Y = np.meshgrid(times, frequencies)

# 5. Plot the 3D surface
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

# Plot a surface. The facecolors argument can map the height (Z) to a color map (like a mountain map)
surf = ax.plot_surface(X, Y, D, cmap='viridis', edgecolor='none')

ax.set_xlabel('Time (sec)')
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
ax.set_zlabel('Amplitude (dB)')
ax.set_title('3D Audio Landscape')

plt.show()

import librosa
import librosa.display
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# 1. Load the audio file
file_path = "test_bird_call3.mp3_2.mp3"  # <-- Change this to your file
y, sr = librosa.load(file_path)

# 2. Create the spectrogram
D = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(librosa.stft(y)), ref=np.max)

# 3. Create time and frequency axes
times = librosa.times_like(D, sr=sr)
frequencies = librosa.fft_frequencies(sr=sr)

# 4. FILTER: Only keep frequencies between 1000-3000 Hz
freq_mask = (frequencies >= 1000) & (frequencies <= 4000)
filtered_frequencies = frequencies[freq_mask]
filtered_D = D[freq_mask, :]  # Keep only the rows (frequencies) we want

# 5. Create meshgrid for the filtered data
X, Y = np.meshgrid(times, filtered_frequencies)

# 6. Plot the 3D surface
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

# Create the surface plot
surf = ax.plot_surface(X, Y, filtered_D, 
                      cmap='viridis', 
                      edgecolor='none', 
                      alpha=0.8,
                      linewidth=0.1)

ax.set_xlabel('Time (sec)')
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
ax.set_zlabel('Amplitude (dB)')
ax.set_title('3D Audio Landscape (1000-3000 Hz)')
ax.set_ylim(1000, 4000)  # Ensure Y-axis shows our range

# Add a color bar
fig.colorbar(surf, ax=ax, shrink=0.5, aspect=5, label='Amplitude (dB)')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Print some info about the filtered data
print(f"Original frequency range: {frequencies[0]:.1f} - {frequencies[-1]:.1f} Hz")
print(f"Filtered frequency range: {filtered_frequencies[0]:.1f} - {filtered_frequencies[-1]:.1f} Hz")
print(f"Filtered spectrogram shape: {filtered_D.shape}")

Filtered frequency range: 1001.3 - 3994.4 Hz
Filtered spectrogram shape: (279, 191)

import librosa
import librosa.display
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# 1. Load the audio file
file_path = "test_bird_call1.mp3"  # <-- Change this
y, sr = librosa.load(file_path)

# 2. Create the spectrogram (limited to 1000-3000 Hz)
D = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(librosa.stft(y)), ref=np.max)
times = librosa.times_like(D, sr=sr)
frequencies = librosa.fft_frequencies(sr=sr)

# Filter to 1000-3000 Hz range
freq_mask = (frequencies >= 1000) & (frequencies <= 3000)
filtered_frequencies = frequencies[freq_mask]
filtered_D = D[freq_mask, :]

# 3. Find the GLOBAL maximum amplitude point
max_amplitude = np.max(filtered_D)
max_time_idx, max_freq_idx = np.unravel_index(np.argmax(filtered_D), filtered_D.shape)
max_time = times[max_time_idx]
max_freq = filtered_frequencies[max_freq_idx]

print("=== GLOBAL MAXIMUM ===")
print(f"Max Amplitude: {max_amplitude:.2f} dB")
print(f"Time: {max_time:.2f} seconds")
print(f"Frequency: {max_freq:.0f} Hz")
print(f"Position: Time index {max_time_idx}, Frequency index {max_freq_idx}")

# 4. Find TOP 5 peak points
def find_peak_points(spectrogram, n_peaks=5):
    """Find the top N peak points in the spectrogram"""
    flat_indices = np.argsort(spectrogram.flatten())[-n_peaks:]  # Get indices of top N values
    peak_indices = np.unravel_index(flat_indices, spectrogram.shape)
    
    peaks = []
    for i in range(n_peaks):
        freq_idx, time_idx = peak_indices[0][i], peak_indices[1][i]
        amplitude = spectrogram[freq_idx, time_idx]
        peaks.append({
            'amplitude': amplitude,
            'time_idx': time_idx,
            'freq_idx': freq_idx,
            'time': times[time_idx],
            'frequency': filtered_frequencies[freq_idx]
        })
    
    return peaks

# Get top 5 peaks
top_peaks = find_peak_points(filtered_D, n_peaks=5)

print("\n=== TOP 5 PEAK POINTS ===")
for i, peak in enumerate(top_peaks):
    print(f"Peak #{i+1}:")
    print(f"  Amplitude: {peak['amplitude']:.2f} dB")
    print(f"  Time: {peak['time']:.2f} sec")
    print(f"  Frequency: {peak['frequency']:.0f} Hz")
    print()

# 5. Create the 3D plot with highlighted peaks
X, Y = np.meshgrid(times, filtered_frequencies)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16, 12))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

# Plot the surface
surf = ax.plot_surface(X, Y, filtered_D, 
                      cmap='viridis', 
                      alpha=0.7,
                      edgecolor='none',
                      linewidth=0.1)

# Highlight the peak points with red markers
peak_times = [peak['time'] for peak in top_peaks]
peak_freqs = [peak['frequency'] for peak in top_peaks]
peak_amps = [peak['amplitude'] for peak in top_peaks]

ax.scatter(peak_times, peak_freqs, peak_amps, 
          color='red', s=100, marker='o', edgecolors='black', linewidth=2, label='Peak Points')

# Highlight the global maximum with a special marker
ax.scatter([max_time], [max_freq], [max_amplitude], 
          color='gold', s=200, marker='*', edgecolors='black', linewidth=2, label='Global Max')

ax.set_xlabel('Time (sec)')
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
ax.set_ylabel('Amplitude (dB)')
ax.set_title('Audio Pattern Analysis with Peak Detection (1000-3000 Hz)')
ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import librosa
import librosa.display
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# 1. Load the audio file
file_path = "test_bird_call4.mp3"
y, sr = librosa.load(file_path)

# 2. Create the spectrogram (limited to 600-900 Hz)
D = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(librosa.stft(y)), ref=np.max)
times = librosa.times_like(D, sr=sr)
frequencies = librosa.fft_frequencies(sr=sr)

# Filter to 600-900 Hz range
freq_mask = (frequencies >= 600) & (frequencies <= 900)
filtered_frequencies = frequencies[freq_mask]
filtered_D = D[freq_mask, :]

print(f"Filtered spectrogram shape: {filtered_D.shape} (frequencies x times)")
print(f"Number of frequency bins: {len(filtered_frequencies)}")
print(f"Number of time frames: {len(times)}")

# 3. FILTER AMPLITUDE: Only consider values between -40 and -10 dB
amplitude_mask = (filtered_D >= -40) & (filtered_D <= -10)
filtered_D_range = np.where(amplitude_mask, filtered_D, -np.inf)  # Set unwanted values to -inf

print(f"Original amplitude range: {np.min(filtered_D):.2f} to {np.max(filtered_D):.2f} dB")

# 4. Find the GLOBAL maximum amplitude point within the desired range
if np.max(filtered_D_range) > -np.inf:  # Check if there are valid points
    max_amplitude = np.max(filtered_D_range)
    max_freq_idx, max_time_idx = np.unravel_index(np.argmax(filtered_D_range), filtered_D_range.shape)
    max_time = times[max_time_idx]
    max_freq = filtered_frequencies[max_freq_idx]
    
    print("=== GLOBAL MAXIMUM (-40 to -10 dB range) ===")
    print(f"Max Amplitude: {max_amplitude:.2f} dB")
    print(f"Time: {max_time:.2f} seconds")
    print(f"Frequency: {max_freq:.0f} Hz")
    print(f"Position: Frequency index {max_freq_idx}, Time index {max_time_idx}")
else:
    print("No points found in the amplitude range -40 to -10 dB!")
    max_amplitude = -10  # Default value for plotting
    max_time = times[len(times)//2]
    max_freq = filtered_frequencies[len(filtered_frequencies)//2]

# 5. Find TOP 5 peak points within the desired amplitude range
def find_peak_points_in_range(spectrogram, amplitude_min=-40, amplitude_max=-10, n_peaks=5):
    """Find the top N peak points within a specific amplitude range"""
    # Create mask for amplitude range
    range_mask = (spectrogram >= amplitude_min) & (spectrogram <= amplitude_max)
    
    if not np.any(range_mask):
        print(f"No points found in amplitude range {amplitude_min} to {amplitude_max} dB")
        return []
    
    # Apply mask and get valid values
    valid_indices = np.where(range_mask)
    valid_values = spectrogram[valid_indices]
    
    # Get top N peaks from valid values
    if len(valid_values) < n_peaks:
        n_peaks = len(valid_values)
    
    top_indices = np.argsort(valid_values)[-n_peaks:]
    
    peaks = []
    for idx in top_indices:
        freq_idx = valid_indices[0][idx]
        time_idx = valid_indices[1][idx]
        amplitude = spectrogram[freq_idx, time_idx]
        peaks.append({
            'amplitude': amplitude,
            'time_idx': time_idx,
            'freq_idx': freq_idx,
            'time': times[time_idx],
            'frequency': filtered_frequencies[freq_idx]
        })
    
    return peaks

# Get top 5 peaks within amplitude range
top_peaks = find_peak_points_in_range(filtered_D, amplitude_min=-40, amplitude_max=-10, n_peaks=5)

print(f"\n=== TOP {len(top_peaks)} PEAK POINTS (-40 to -10 dB) ===")
for i, peak in enumerate(top_peaks):
    print(f"Peak #{i+1}:")
    print(f"  Amplitude: {peak['amplitude']:.2f} dB")
    print(f"  Time: {peak['time']:.2f} sec")
    print(f"  Frequency: {peak['frequency']:.0f} Hz")
    print()

# 6. Create the 3D plot with amplitude range focus
X, Y = np.meshgrid(times, filtered_frequencies)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16, 12))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

# Plot the surface, but clip the amplitude range for better visualization
surf = ax.plot_surface(X, Y, np.clip(filtered_D, -40, -10), 
                      cmap='viridis', 
                      alpha=0.7,
                      edgecolor='none',
                      linewidth=0.1,
                      vmin=-40, vmax=-10)  # Set color scale limits

# Highlight the peak points within range
if top_peaks:
    peak_times = [peak['time'] for peak in top_peaks]
    peak_freqs = [peak['frequency'] for peak in top_peaks]
    peak_amps = [peak['amplitude'] for peak in top_peaks]
    
    ax.scatter(peak_times, peak_freqs, peak_amps, 
              color='red', s=100, marker='o', edgecolors='black', linewidth=2, label='Peak Points')

# Highlight the global maximum within range
if np.max(filtered_D_range) > -np.inf:
    ax.scatter([max_time], [max_freq], [max_amplitude], 
              color='gold', s=200, marker='*', edgecolors='black', linewidth=2, label='Global Max')

# Set axis limits to focus on your desired amplitude range
ax.set_zlim(-40, -10)

ax.set_xlabel('Time (sec)')
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency (Hz)')
ax.set_zlabel('Amplitude (dB)')
ax.set_title('Audio Pattern Analysis (600-900 Hz, Amplitude: -40 to -10 dB)')
ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# 7. Additional analysis: Show amplitude distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.hist(filtered_D.flatten(), bins=50, alpha=0.7, edgecolor='black')
